flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn run-close reconstruction truth into governance truth that is append-safe and explicitly closed"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than run reconstruction and narrower than final-verdict publication"]
    G3["Answer where the platform appends closure truth and how it marks the run as formally closed"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is not that the platform is done enough"]
    E2["The entry is run report plus reconciliation truth already committed, with the earlier spine lanes already reconciled under one run scope"]
    E3["The spine observability closure sequence requires run report and reconciliation first, governance append closure next, then non-regression anchors, then later handoff and cost-outcome closure"]
    E4["So this path begins after the exact run story is already known, not before"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Reconciled run-close truth"]
    R2["Governance append corridor"]
    R3["Append log under run scope"]
    R4["Closure marker under run scope"]
    R5["Later verdict and handoff lanes can trust formal closure"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Run identity and run scope"]
    C2["Reconciled closure truth from the previous path"]
    C3["Append-log facts that record the closure progression"]
    C4["The formal close-marker object that declares the run closed"]
    C5["Publication and readback information proving those objects are actually present under the authoritative evidence scope"]
    C6["The handles and evidence contracts pin the concrete targets: governance append log under the run-scoped governance surface and governance closure marker under the same run scope"]
    C7["The governance-closure verification lane proves append and close-marker surfaces together with the run-completed closure refs"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats run understanding and run closure governance as two different truths"]
    L2["The system is not saying once we can explain the run, closure is obvious"]
    L3["It is saying there is a dedicated append-safe governance boundary where the platform records and marks closure explicitly"]
    L4["That makes the current wired system look controlled rather than merely observable"]
    L5["It also matches the broader authority style: no phase is valid without explicit proof obligations, and closure is not allowed to rest on informal operator interpretation"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["This path is materially seated in the current wired platform"]
    S2["The concrete durable surfaces are pinned in object storage under the run evidence scope: governance append log and governance closure marker"]
    S3["This was not merely planned: the governance-closure verification lane is already closed green and records the actual governance projection outputs under the concrete run scope"]
    S4["The same closure note says these surfaces passed schema, run-scope, and order checks"]
    S5["So this boundary is already a real operated closure lane in the current wired platform, not just a diagram idea"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform refuses two weak shortcuts: the run report exists as proxy for formal closure, and a mutable summary object as substitute for append-safe governance history plus close marker"]
    Y2["That is why the closure plan includes a dedicated governance-append and closure-marker verification lane"]
    Y3["Its definition of done requires that the governance append log and closure marker are committed and append-safe"]
    Y4["The successful governance-closure verification reinforces the same intent: it did not simply check that files existed; it verified schema, run-scope, and ordering coverage before allowing the phase to advance"]
    Y5["That is exactly what you would expect from a system that wants governance closure to be an explicit truth boundary rather than a cosmetic artifact"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The spine observability closure contract shapes the requirement: run report and reconciliation committed, governance append closure committed, and non-regression anchor pack emitted"]
    X2["The handles and evidence contract shapes the concrete surfaces: append-log path pattern and close-marker path pattern"]
    X3["The governance-closure execution contract shapes the lane itself: dedicated verification lane for append and close-marker surfaces and fail-closed blocker family for governance append or closure-marker failure"]
    X4["The broader design authority shapes the posture: explicit proof obligations, drift watch on evidence gaps, and post-run audit ritual before advancing"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds another formal closure boundary after reconstruction"]
    T2["That costs append-safe governance mechanics, one more durable evidence surface, one more ordering and run-scope verification step, and one more explicit blocker family"]
    T3["But that cost buys the ability to answer not just what happened, but whether closure was formally recorded, whether closure history is append-safe, whether the run was actually marked closed under the right scope, and whether later verdict and handoff artifacts are built on real closure marker rather than informal assumptions"]
    T4["That matters directly for the meta-goal because a serious reviewer will trust the system more if closure is explicitly governed and durable, not only summarized"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still reconstruct the run, produce receipts, and maybe even publish a later verdict"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to where formal closure was appended"]
    N3["It loses a clean answer to what marks the run as closed"]
    N4["It loses a clean answer to whether closure history is append-safe"]
    N5["It loses a clean answer to whether later verdict and handoff lanes are building on explicit closure truth or just on the existence of a report"]
    N6["That would weaken A immediately because the platform could explain the run but would have no explicit owner for formal governance closure itself"]
    N7["The phase plan rejects exactly that looseness by making governance append and close-marker verification a dedicated lane"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Append-safe governance truth exists"]
    O2["Formal run-close marker exists under the run evidence scope"]
    O3["Both surfaces are schema-correct, run-scope-correct, and order-safe"]
    O4["Owned outcome: append-safe governance truth plus formal run-close marker"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for turning reconstructed run truth into append-safe governance closure before final-verdict publication advances"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>append log and close marker are designed closure objects, not optional reporting extras"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>this boundary is concretely seated in named run-scope governance surfaces and an already executed governance-closure verification lane"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>this path is governed by append-log and close-marker surface contracts, dedicated governance verification, run-scope correctness, ordering correctness, and append-safe closure obligations"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the platform already knows a run report is not the same as formal closure, which is why close-marker and governance append verification are explicit proof objects rather than assumptions"]
    A6["A-level meaning:<br/>the platform does not merely understand a run; it can record and mark closure formally under governed durable surfaces"]
  end

